Hi guys.

I'm trying to render an animated background for my game. The entire spritesheet has a 828x2864 dimension. 

It is composed of 8 frames, so to render it properly i need to draw it from a rectangle source of 828x358, starting at location x:0 y:0

In order to avoid declaring a new Rectangle instance at each draw call and to prevent flickering, i just want to displace the rectangle location on the Y-Axis by 358 pixels. Of course, the Y location is resetted to 0 at the end of the 8th frame.

The thing is, its never moving. Nothing changes when i try to use the Offset method. I tried to add all sorts of value, tried to used the Inflates() method with random values, EVERYTHING, and nothing changes or move by a pixel.

In fact, i'm facing two problems : if i declare each time a new Rectangle instance with a new location, all the background is flickering (the spritesheet is properly done, and im not declaring a new Texture2D instance at each time, everything is preloaded, so i assume this comes from the fact im calling new Rectangle2D at each draw). 

And if i want to use a more proper solution such as simply moving the rectangle, the offset method doesnt do anything. Does someone have an idea of what could possibly be the cause ?

Here's an example of what im globally trying to do :

//previously loaded rectangle
MapView = new Rectangle(BackgroundRenderPosX, //0
    BackgroundRenderPosY, //0
    Tilesets.FirstOrDefault().TileWidth, //828
    Tilesets.FirstOrDefault().TileHeight //358
);

public void Update()
{
    if(MapView.Value.Y != Spritesheet.Height) {
        MapView.Value.Offset(0, Tilesets.FirstOrDefault().TileHeight);
    }
    else
    {
        MapView.Value.Offset(0, -SpriteSheet.Height);
    }  
}

It is not the real source code, but it really represents what i'm trying to do. Offset() just wont move my rectangle position.

Thanks in advance,

Rational

I'm having issues on iOS with quick taps, when there is only one Press followed by one Release event.

The events are both coming in rapid succession that leaves no time for GetState() to be called, therefore, the event is removed by this line:
if (existingTouch.State == TouchLocationState.Pressed && touch.State == TouchLocationState.Released)
{
   state.RemoveAt(i);
}

Not sure what the easy fix for this is without a queue.
You can repro by tapping rapidly on an iOS device.

